resources.name: Search (by content_type)
resources.description:
To search for entries with a specific content type, set the content_type URI query parameter to the ID you want to search for.

Note: When querying entries and using search filters based on fields or ordering by fields you must specify this parameter. You can only specify one value for content_type at a time.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/content-type](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/content-type)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}
`

resources.name: Search
resources.description:
# Search parameters
You can use a variety of query parameters to search and filter items in the response from any collection endpoint including entries, content types and assets.

resources.name: Search (Select operator)
resources.description:
The select operator allows you to choose what fields to return from an entity. You can choose multiple values by combining comma separated operators.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/select-operator](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/select-operator)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}&select={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Array Equality/Inequality)
resources.description:
The equality/inequality operators also work with array fields:

- **Equality**: If one of the items in an array matches the searched term, then it returns the entry.
- **Inequality**: If one of the fields in an array matches the searched term, then the entry is not returned.

Note: As the query filters by a field, you need to specify a content type.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/array-equality-inequality](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/array-equality-inequality)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}&fields.{field_id}={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Array with multiple values)
resources.description:
It's possible to use the **[all]** operator to retrieve entries matching a specific set of values (e.g. **fields.likes[all]=flowers,accessories**)

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/array-with-multiple-values](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/array-with-multiple-values)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}&fields.{field_id}[all]={values}
`

resources.name: Search (Inclusion IN)
resources.description:
You can filter a field by multiple values with the **[in]** operator. When applied to an array value there must be at least one matching item. Similarly, when including a field value, you need to specify a Content type.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/inclusion](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/inclusion)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}&{attribute}[in]={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Exclusion not IN)
resources.description:
You can filter a field by multiple values with the **[nin]** operator. When applied to an array value there must be at least one not matching item. Similarly, when including a field value, you need to specify a content type.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/exclusion](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/exclusion)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}&{attribute}[nin]={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Existence)
resources.description:
You can check for the presence of a field using the **[exists]** operator. It checks whether a certain field is defined (i.e. it has any value) or not.

If the field is not defined, it will not be present in the JSON payload and the operator will consider it non-existent.

You can pass **true** or **false** as a parameter depending on if you want to retrieve entries where the field exists (**true**) or does not exist (**false**). Please note that the parameter is case sensitive, **True** or **False** are not valid values.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/existence](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/existence)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}&{attribute}[exists]={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Ranges)
resources.description:
Four range operators are available that you can apply to date and number fields:

- **[lt]**: Less than.
- **[lte]**: Less than or equal to.
- **[gt]**: Greater than.
- **[gte]**: Greater than or equal to.

When applied to field values, you must specify the content type in the query.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/ranges](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/ranges)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&{attribute}[gte]={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Full text)
resources.description:
Global, described in this section

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/full-text-search](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/full-text-search)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&query={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Full text on field)
resources.description:
With the **[match]** operator you can do a full-text search restricted to the content of a specific field. The way full-text search behaves on one field is the same as in the global full-text search and the documentation for the global full-text search also applies here, with the particularity that matches on other fields of the entries or assets won't be considered. As with the global search, you can enabled phrase search if you wrap the input search terms in double quoutes (").

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/full-text-search-on-a-field](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/full-text-search-on-a-field)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}&fields.{field_id}[match]={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Location proximty)
resources.description:
You can use a proximity search on location-enabled content to find results in a specified geographical area.

Note: Queries that include exact coordinates can't take advantage of our caching layer. With many use cases it should be enough to round the coordinates to 3 decimal places (an accuracy of about 300m), 2 decimal places (an accuracy of about 1km) or more to improve your cache hit rates.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/location-proximity-search](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/location-proximity-search)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&fields.center[near]={coordinate}&content_type={content_type}
`

resources.name: Search (Locations in a bounding object)
resources.description:
When displaying content on a map it's more resource efficient to retrieve only content that is in the current visible map area. For these cases, use the within operator.

Similar to the 'near me' use case, this lets you search for locations that are within the specific area on the map and can be useful for finding related entries in the vicinity of another entry.

There are two ways to search for nearby locations.

1. Using a bounding rectangle:
2. Using a bounding circle:

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/locations-in-a-bounding-object](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/locations-in-a-bounding-object)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&fields.center[within]={rectangle}&content_type={content_type}
`

resources.name: Search (Links to entry)
resources.description:
To search for entries which have a field linking to a specific entry, set the links_to_entry URI query parameter to the ID you want to search for.

NOTE: For most use cases it is more performant to query based on a content type's reference field if the desired content type is known. See Search on references for an example query

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/links-to-entry](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/links-to-entry)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&links_to_entry={entry_id}
`

resources.name: Search (Links to asset)
resources.description:
To search for entries which have a field linking to a specific asset, set the **links_to_asset** URI query parameter to the ID you want to search for.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/links-to-asset](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/links-to-asset)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&links_to_asset={asset_id}
`

resources.name: Search (Order)
resources.description:
You can order items in the response by specifying the order search parameter. You can use sys properties (such as sys.createdAt) or field values (such as fields.myCustomDateField) for ordering.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/order](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/order)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&order={attribute}
`

resources.name: Search (Order reverse)
resources.description:
You can reverse the sort order by prefixing the field with a **-** symbol.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/reverse-order](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/reverse-order)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&order=-{attribute}
`

resources.name: Search (Order with multiple parameters)
resources.description:
You can order items by specifying the order parameter with attributes(**attribute**, **attribute2**). Prefix the field with a **-** sign to reverse the sort order of the attribute.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/order-with-multiple-parameters](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/order-with-multiple-parameters)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&order={attribute},{attribute2}
`

resources.name: Search (Limit - Skip)
resources.description:
#Limit
You can specify the maximum number of results as a limit search parameter.

Note: The maximum number of entries returned by the API is 1000. The API will throw a BadRequestError for values higher than 1000 and values other than an integer. The default number of entries returned by the API is 100.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/limit](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/limit)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&limit={value}
`

#Skip
You can specify an offset with the skip search parameter.

Note: The API will throw a BadRequestError for values less than 0 or values other than an integer.

By combining skip and limit you can paginate through results:

Page 1: skip=0, limit=15 Page 2: skip=15, limit=15 Page 3: skip=30, limit=15 etc.


[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/skip](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/skip)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&skip={value}
`

resources.name: Search (Filtering assets by MIME type)
resources.description:
You can filter assets by their MIME type group by using the mimetype_group query parameter. Valid groups are **attachment**, **plaintext**, **image**, **audio**, **video**, **richtext**, **presentation**, **spreadsheet**, **pdfdocument**, **archive**, **code** and **markup**. By default, the API will return all assets.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/filtering-assets-by-mime-type](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/filtering-assets-by-mime-type)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/assets?access_token={access_token}&mimetype_group={mimetype_group}
`

resources.name: Search (Search on references)
resources.description:
You can search for entries based on the values of referenced entries.

For example, if you want to find products of a particular brand, you can use search on references to find the products with one API request.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/search-on-references](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/search-parameters/search-on-references)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&content_type={content_type}&fields.{reference_field}.sys.contentType.sys.id={reference_content_type}&fields.{reference_field}.fields.{search_field}[match]={search_value}
`

resources.name: Space
resources.description:
All content and assets in Contentful belong to a space. You will generally have at least one space for a project, but use separate spaces for testing or staging.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/spaces](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/spaces "https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/spaces")

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}?access_token={access_token}
`

resources.name: Content Types
resources.description:
# Content types

Defining a content type is a fundamental step in powering your applications with Contentful. A content type consists of a set of fields and other information, read this guide to learn more about modelling your content.

resources.name: Entries Collection
resources.description:
In the JSON response of a successful query, linked items are placed in the includes array, when not already fetched in the items array.

Note: Links in the Delivery API will always only resolve to published entries. Unresolved items will not be present in the includes array. The Preview API will include draft entries with the same caveat that unresolved links will not appear in the includes array.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/entries/entries-collection](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/entries/entries-collection)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}
`

resources.name: Entries
resources.description:
# Entries
Entries represent anything defined as a Content Type in a space.

Entries can have link fields that point to other entries or assets. You can learn more about links in our concept guide.

resources.name: Entry
resources.description:
The include array is not applicable while retrieving a single entry.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/entries/entry](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/entries/entry)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries/{entry_id}?access_token={access_token}
`

resources.name: Assets
resources.description:
# Assets
Assets are the binary files in a space. An asset can be any file type and are usually attached to entries with links.

You can localize assets by providing separate files for each locale. Assets which are not localized are available as a single file under the default locale.

When you query for entries which contain links to assets then all assets are included by default.

resources.name: Asset keys
resources.description:
# Assets
Assets are the binary files in a space. An asset can be any file type and are usually attached to entries with links.

You can localize assets by providing separate files for each locale. Assets which are not localized are available as a single file under the default locale.

When you query for entries which contain links to assets then all assets are included by default.

resources.name: Locales
resources.description:
# Locales
Locales allow you to define translatable content for assets and entries. A locale includes the following properties:

- **name**: A human readable identifier for a locale. For example, 'British English'.
- **code**: An identifier used to differentiate translated content in API responses. For example, 'en-GB'.
- **fallbackCode**: The code of the locale to use if there is no translated content for the requested locale. For example, en-US. You can set it to null if you don't want a default locale. This can only be set via the API, and not with the web app or SDKs.

resources.name: Retrieval of linked items
resources.description:
When you have related content (e.g. entries with links to image assets) it's possible to include both search results and related data in a single request. Using the include parameter, you can specify the number of levels to resolve.

The maximum number of levels is 10. The API will throw a BadRequestError for higher values or values other than an integer. The default number, if the parameter is not specified, is 1. To omit linked items, specify include as 0.

If the standard items array has not already retrieved the linked entries, they will be in the includes.Entry array. Linked assets are inside the includes.Asset array.

Note: The include parameter resolves links between entries and assets within a space. Links between content types within a space are not included in the response.

Note: The include parameter is only available for the entry collection endpoint /spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/links/retrieval-of-linked-items](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/links/retrieval-of-linked-items)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&include={include}
`

resources.name: Links
resources.description:
# Links
Links are a powerful way to model relationships between content entries and assets. You can learn more about links in our concept guide.

resources.name: Links to a specific item
resources.description:
If you want to retrieve all items linked to a specific entry, the query URL should filter entries on their specific content_type, linking_field (field to link items) and entry_id from the target entry.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/links/links-to-a-specific-item](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/links/links-to-a-specific-item)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries?access_token={access_token}&include={value}&content_type={content_type}&fields.{linking_field}.sys.id={target_entry_id}
`

resources.name: Retrieve localized entries
resources.description:
You can specify a locale for entries using the locale URI query parameter.

The locale parameter must be the code of a locale in the space you're querying, or the wildcard value *. If you don't specify a locale, the default locale of the space is used.

If there's no content available for the requested locale the API will try the fallback locale of the requested locale.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/localization/retrieve-localized-entries](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/localization/retrieve-localized-entries)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/environments/{environment_id}/entries/{entry_id}?access_token={access_token}&locale={locale}
`

resources.name: Initial synchronization
resources.description:
A client syncs content by using the sync endpoint. A single sync consists of one or more pages, each a separate request and response.

The first time a client synchronizes content it sends a request to the sync endpoint with the URI query parameter initial set to true.

You should only sync with initial=true for the initial sync when a client has no existing content. This transfers all content from a space, but does not contain content deleted from fields or deleted assets and content entries.

The limit parameter sets the page size for the number of retrieved entries. The limit is useful when you have very large content entries and reach the maximum response size limit. This limit is then encoded in the synchronization token and used for all following synchronizations.

Sync only contains content from the master environment and is not containing deltas from sandbox environments.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization/initial-synchronization](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization/initial-synchronization)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/sync?access_token={access_token}&initial=true&type={type}&limit={limit}
`

resources.name: Synchronization
resources.description:
The Sync API allows you to keep a local copy of all content in a space up-to-date via delta updates, or only the content that has changed.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization)

resources.name: Next Sync
resources.description:
A client syncs content by using the sync endpoint. A single sync consists of one or more pages, each a separate request and response.

The first time a client synchronizes content it sends a request to the sync endpoint with the URI query parameter initial set to true.

You should only sync with initial=true for the initial sync when a client has no existing content. This transfers all content from a space, but does not contain content deleted from fields or deleted assets and content entries.

The limit parameter sets the page size for the number of retrieved entries. The limit is useful when you have very large content entries and reach the maximum response size limit. This limit is then encoded in the synchronization token and used for all following synchronizations.

Sync only contains content from the master environment and is not containing deltas from sandbox environments.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization/initial-synchronization](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization/initial-synchronization)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/sync?access_token={access_token}&initial=true&type={type}&limit={limit}
`

resources.name: Initial synchronization of entries of a specific content type
resources.description:
For entries, you can also specify a content_type parameter. When specifying content_type you must specify type as Entry (meaning there will be no deletions). You can only specify the type and content_type parameter at the initial sync along with the initial parameter. Any subsequent syncs will only include the types you have specified. If you want to sync entries by content type you should separately subscribe to a Deletion or DeletedEntry sync to be notified when entries are deleted.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization/initial-synchronization-of-entries-of-a-specific-content-type](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization/initial-synchronization-of-entries-of-a-specific-content-type)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/sync?access_token={access_token}&initial=true&type=Entry&content_type={content_type}&limit={limit}
`

resources.name: Pagination and subsequent syncs
resources.description:
Synchronization responses contain either a **nextPageUrl** or **nextSyncUrl** attribute. If there is more content for the current sync, **nextPageUrl** will contain an URL with a **sync_token** which will retrieve the next page. This continues until you have retrieved all content.

At this point, the response will contain a **nextSyncUrl** which you use to make requests in the future and retrieve delta updates between the current content on Contentful and what you retrieved with your last sync request. Upon completion, you will receive a new **nextSyncUrl** which you can again use for future updates.

If a client loses the **nextSyncUrl**, the client should delete its local content and perform an initial synchronization again.

NOTE: The initial query with **sync_token** will persist across subsequent syncs.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization/pagination-and-subsequent-syncs](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-delivery-api/#/reference/synchronization/pagination-and-subsequent-syncs)

`
curl --include --request GET https://cdn.contentful.com/spaces/{space_id}/sync?access_token={access_token}&sync_token={sync_token}
`

resources.name: Querying content based on a set of tags
Spaces collection
resources.description:
Spaces are containers for content types and content, and API clients can fetch data from one or more spaces. You can be a member of multiple organizations, and owner and admin roles in the organization can create spaces in organizations.

When you sign up to Contentul for the first time, you create a new organization. When you're invited to an existing organization, you become a member of that organization.

Note: If you have a single organization, any space you create will be automatically associated with that organization. If you're an admin or an owner in multiple organizations you need to pass the ID of the organization with the X-Contentful-Organization header that you want to create the space in.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-management-api/#/reference/spaces/spaces-collection](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-management-api/#/reference/spaces/spaces-collection)

`
curl --include --request GET --header 'Authorization: Bearer <cma_token>' https://api.contentful.com/spaces
`

resources.name: CMA
resources.description:
Contentful's Content Management API (CMA) helps you manage content in your spaces. To learn more about how to model your content, read our modeling guide.

Note: You can use the CMA to deliver and manage content, but you shouldn't use it to deliver large amounts of content and instead use the Content Delivery API. The structure of responses from the CMA differs from the CDA as GET responses retrieve the entirety of items (i.e. all localized and unpublished content).

resources.name: Create Space
resources.description:
Create a new space, specifying attributes in the request body.

[https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-management-api/#/reference/spaces/space](https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-management-api/#/reference/spaces/space)

`
curl --include --request POST --header 'Authorization: Bearer <cma_token>' --header 'Content-Type: application/vnd.contentful.management.v1+json' --header 'X-Contentful-Organization: 1PLOOEmTI2S1NYald2TemO' --data-binary '{
       "name": "Example Space",
       "defaultLocale": "en"
     }' https://api.contentful.com/spaces
`

Search (Location bounding object)
resources.description:
1. Using a bounding rectangle:
To search for locations within a rectangle area object, use the structure field.center[within]=latitude1,longitude1,latitude2,longitude2, where:

latitude1 and longitude1 refer to the coordinates of the bottom left corner of the rectangle.

latitude2 and longitude2 refer to the coordinates of the top right corner of the rectangle.

2. Using a bounding circle:
The structure field.center[within]=latitute,longitude,radius will return entries included in the circle with fields.center of the given latitude, longitude and radius (in km).

https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/content-preview-api/#/reference/search-parameters/locations-in-a-bounding-object

resources.name: Change the resizing behavior
resources.description:
fit Possible values:

pad: Resize the image to the specified dimensions, padding the image if needed.
fill: Resize the image to the specified dimensions, cropping the image if needed.
scale: Resize the image to the specified dimensions, changing the original aspect ratio if needed.
crop: Crop a part of the original image to fit into the specified dimensions.
thumb: Create a thumbnail from the image.

https://www.contentful.com/developers/docs/references/images-api/#/reference/resizing-&-cropping/change-the-resizing-behavior

resources.name: Specify focus area
resources.description:

top_right, top_left, bottom_right, bottom_left.
